  "body": "/area controller-manager\r\n/area extensibility\r\n/kind bug\r\n/sig apimachinery\r\n\r\n**What happened**:\r\nThe kube-controller-manager is unable to start when it cannot discover the APIs of API server extensions. Precisely, the `APIService` object indicated availability although the extended API server was not running anymore. Restarting the kube-controller-manager failed for the mentioned reason.\r\n\r\n**What you expected to happen**:\r\nThe `APIService` object should not indicate availability if the respective API server is not running. Not sure if the kube-controller-manager could ignore APIs it cannot discover, what does it actually need to do with them? Actually, the only way to make the kube-controller-manager start again is to temporarily de-register the extended API, start it, and register it again.\r\n\r\n**How to reproduce it (as minimally and precisely as possible)**:\r\nDeploy a Kubernetes cluster, register an aggregated API server, wait for the `APIService` status to indicate availability, then delete the aggregated API server pod and restart the kube-controller-manager. It will \r\n\r\n**Environment**:\r\n- Kubernetes version (use `kubectl version`): 1.10.4\r\n",
